ints a new portrait of polar voyagers, one that removes them from the icy backdrop of the Arctic and sets them within the tempests of American cultural life. With chronological chapters featuring emblematic Arctic explorers—including Elisha Kent Kane, Charles Hall, and Robert Peary—The Coldest Crucible reveals why the North Pole, a region so geographically removed from Americans, became an iconic destination for discovery.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aExplorerszUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aSciencezUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aScientistszUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh1 aCook, Frederick, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGreely, Adolphus, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHall, Charles, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHayes, Isaac, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKane, Elisha Kent, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPeary, Robert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWellman, Walter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311063538640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226721873423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226721873.jpg  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles